00:00:56.750 --> 00:00:59.120
I'll give you a little
bit of background of,

00:00:59.120 --> 00:01:00.670
you know, how this thing started.

00:01:00.670 --> 00:01:05.020
Initially, it was a magazine
story idea that I sent

00:01:05.020 --> 00:01:07.950
to a very prominent magazine.

00:01:07.950 --> 00:01:12.190
I sent a two to three
paragraph pitch to a gentleman,

00:01:12.190 --> 00:01:15.070
and he got back to me and
said, I really like this,

00:01:15.070 --> 00:01:17.190
but we're not going to use it,

00:01:17.190 --> 00:01:20.650
because I think you have
something so much bigger here.

00:01:20.650 --> 00:01:24.550
And he put me in touch with
some people who were veterans

00:01:24.550 --> 00:01:26.520
of the publishing industry.

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:29.100
And they said, wow, this
is a wonderful idea,

00:01:29.100 --> 00:01:33.200
are you up to taking a two to
three paragraph magazine proposal

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:37.010
and turning it into an
80-page book proposal?

00:01:37.010 --> 00:01:40.440
And so from there, was
just off and running.

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:46.320
The seeds of this story were
planted way back in 1982 for me.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:48.100
And this was around the time

00:01:48.100 --> 00:01:52.130
that this team was accomplishing
some magnificent things

00:01:52.130 --> 00:01:54.110
on the basketball court.

00:01:54.110 --> 00:01:55.920
I grew up in Brooklyn, New York,

00:01:55.920 --> 00:01:59.550
and there was a basketball court
directly behind my building.

00:01:59.550 --> 00:02:05.490
And we were basketball
enthusiasts, junkies, morons,

00:02:05.490 --> 00:02:07.080
whatever you want to call it.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:08.390
We were out there every day.

00:02:08.390 --> 00:02:10.750
If it was snowing, we
were shoveling snow.

00:02:10.750 --> 00:02:14.230
We not only played but
we debated and we argued,

00:02:14.230 --> 00:02:15.960
everything that's basketball
related.

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:18.610
And for people in here that
are familiar with folks

00:02:18.610 --> 00:02:21.630
from New York City, we were
loud, we were arrogant,

00:02:21.630 --> 00:02:23.740
and we thought we knew everything.

00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:27.150
So we're 12 years old, and we're
talking about our favorite players

00:02:27.150 --> 00:02:30.660
from New York, and why New
York is the king of basketball.

00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:33.800
So we're talking about Bernard
King for the New York Knicks

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:36.190
who was our favorite
player at the time.

00:02:36.190 --> 00:02:39.170
We're talking about Julius
Erving, the Great Doctor Jay was

00:02:39.170 --> 00:02:41.420
from Long Island, who we loved.

00:02:41.420 --> 00:02:45.630
Tiny Archibald, the only player
to ever lead the NBA in assists

00:02:45.630 --> 00:02:47.830
and scoring in the same year.

00:02:47.830 --> 00:02:52.960
Guys by the name of World be Free,
Vinnie the Microwave Johnson.

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:57.290
We're even going back to Bob Cousy,
the Great Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.

00:02:57.290 --> 00:02:58.590
If you were lucky enough,

00:02:58.590 --> 00:03:00.790
you saw him wondering the
halls, he's here today.

00:03:00.790 --> 00:03:03.580
And we're talking about
all these players,

00:03:03.580 --> 00:03:08.910
and they are older neighborhood
superheroes that we're watching

00:03:08.910 --> 00:03:12.890
and we're seeing play in these
great playground tournaments.

00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:14.620
There was a guy in
high school by the name

00:03:14.620 --> 00:03:17.840
of Chris Mullen, who was awesome.

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:19.300
We loved Chris Mullen.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:23.970
Our personal hero was a guy by the
name of Duane the Pearl Washington,

00:03:23.970 --> 00:03:27.730
who was significant in
turning the Big East Conference

00:03:27.730 --> 00:03:30.090
in Syracuse University basketball

00:03:30.090 --> 00:03:33.240
into the phenomenon
that it later became.

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:35.890
There was a guy by the
name of Walter Berry,

00:03:35.890 --> 00:03:38.790
who went on to become the National
Player of the Year at St. John's,

00:03:38.790 --> 00:03:40.520
leading them to the Final Four.

00:03:40.520 --> 00:03:43.500
These were guys we saw around
the neighborhood and playing.

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:49.430
And there were other guys our
own age who we're hearing about.

00:03:49.430 --> 00:03:51.440
There was a guy by the
name of Kenny Anderson,

00:03:51.440 --> 00:03:55.150
and we called him Kenny the Kid,
or Kenny Ice, who was tearing

00:03:55.150 --> 00:03:57.180 position:56%
up the youth playground tournaments.

00:03:57.180 --> 00:04:01.690 position:56%
There was a guy by the name of Malik
Sealy, the great late Malik Sealy.

00:04:01.690 --> 00:04:03.750
And all of these other players.

00:04:03.750 --> 00:04:05.970
We heard about these brothers

00:04:05.970 --> 00:04:09.830
in Coney Island called the Marbury
Brothers, Norman and Jou-Jou,

00:04:09.830 --> 00:04:11.460
and a bunch of other ones.

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:15.580
And little did we know that their
younger brother, Stephon Marbury,

00:04:15.580 --> 00:04:17.860
would go on to surpass them all.

00:04:17.860 --> 00:04:19.380
And so we're having
this conversation

00:04:19.380 --> 00:04:22.360 position:56%
about how great New York is, and
there's an older gentleman who lives

00:04:22.360 --> 00:04:25.670
in my building, and he was
probably in his young 20s.

00:04:25.670 --> 00:04:28.320
He was an excellent
playground basketball player

00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:29.810
and we used to go watch him play.

00:04:29.810 --> 00:04:34.100
And he said, yeah, New York's
the king of basketball,

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:37.480
but the greatest team I ever
saw was a high school team

00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:41.680
from Baltimore called Dunbar.

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:47.270
And so we're watching the
Philadelphia 76ers and Doctor Jay

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:51.380
and Larry Bird with the Celtics
and Magic Johnson with the Lakers.

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:52.910
And we said, wait a minute,

00:04:52.910 --> 00:04:57.040
the greatest team you ever saw is
a high school team from Baltimore?

00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:01.020
And he goes on to explain, every
player on the bench is going

00:05:01.020 --> 00:05:03.470
to play Division I basketball.

00:05:03.470 --> 00:05:06.340
They have the number one high
school player in the country

00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:08.100
by the name of Reggie Williams.

00:05:08.100 --> 00:05:10.840
Wait till you get a chance
to see him in college.

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:12.350
He's six foot seven.

00:05:12.350 --> 00:05:15.130
He can play every position
on the floor.

00:05:15.130 --> 00:05:16.430
He can block shots.

00:05:16.430 --> 00:05:17.730
He can rebound.

00:05:17.730 --> 00:05:19.030
He can shoot jump shots.

00:05:19.030 --> 00:05:20.330
He can pass.

00:05:20.330 --> 00:05:21.630
He's marvelous.

00:05:21.630 --> 00:05:22.930
He's unbelievable.

00:05:22.930 --> 00:05:25.130
But the crazy thing is, he's
not even the best player

00:05:25.130 --> 00:05:27.980
on his own team.

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:31.010
So we're scratching our
head and saying, okay,

00:05:31.010 --> 00:05:32.570
the number one high school player

00:05:32.570 --> 00:05:37.810 position:56%
in the country is not even the best
player on his own team, yeah, right.

00:05:37.810 --> 00:05:39.110
So who is the best player?

00:05:39.110 --> 00:05:41.800
And he said, you're not
going to believe me.

00:05:41.800 --> 00:05:43.370
Come on, man, who is
the best player?

00:05:43.370 --> 00:05:47.610
He says, all right, the best
player is a five-foot midget,

00:05:47.610 --> 00:05:51.760
and his name is Muggsy.

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:53.060
He called him Muggsy.

00:05:53.060 --> 00:05:54.950
And we thought he was lying.

00:05:54.950 --> 00:05:56.250
We thought he was playing with us.

00:05:56.250 --> 00:05:58.750
A couple of years later,

00:05:58.750 --> 00:06:03.630
I'm watching this innovative
cable network with the idea

00:06:03.630 --> 00:06:07.160
of 24-hour sports programming
called ESPN.

00:06:07.160 --> 00:06:12.590
And I'm watching a Wake Forest
University basketball game,

00:06:12.590 --> 00:06:17.600
and I see a 5'3 athletic marvel
unlike anything I've ever seen

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:21.210 position:56%
before by the name of Muggsy Bogues.

00:06:21.210 --> 00:06:26.860
And I screamed to no one in
particular, that's Muggsy.

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:30.550
And so I was in prep school
in Massachusetts at the time.

00:06:30.550 --> 00:06:32.450
And there was a player by
the name of Reggie Lewis

00:06:32.450 --> 00:06:36.930
at Northeastern University, who
was phenomenal, unbelievable,

00:06:36.930 --> 00:06:39.580
tearing up the college
basketball scene.

00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:44.450
And I heard that he couldn't even
start for his own high school team.

00:06:44.450 --> 00:06:46.840
So I did a little digging,
a little bit of research,

00:06:46.840 --> 00:06:49.980
and found out that he
attended Dunbar High School

00:06:49.980 --> 00:06:52.180
with this guy named Muggsy Bogues.

00:06:52.180 --> 00:06:58.490
And so the light bulb went on and
I started to think about this team.

00:06:58.490 --> 00:07:04.490
Reggie Williams and David Wingate
were at Georgetown University

00:07:04.490 --> 00:07:11.460
at the time, at the apex of the
phenomenon known as Hoya Paranoia.

00:07:11.460 --> 00:07:16.430
They delivered John Thompson's
only national championship.

00:07:16.430 --> 00:07:20.400
And Reggie Williams as a
freshman at Georgetown,

00:07:20.400 --> 00:07:23.380
was the most valuable player,
the most outstanding player

00:07:23.380 --> 00:07:28.460 position:56%
in the Final Four when they defeated
an incredibly talented Phi Slama

00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:32.130
Jama team from the University of
Houston that featured future Hall

00:07:32.130 --> 00:07:37.640
of Famers Hakeem Olajuwon, Clyde
Drexler, and a number of others.

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:43.300
Reggie had 19 points and seven
rebounds in the final game.

00:07:43.300 --> 00:07:48.620
And to think that the year before,
this guy was in high school,

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:54.510
just boggles the mind and tells
you how exceptional he was.

00:07:54.510 --> 00:07:57.760
And so this idea had been
marinating for a while,

00:07:57.760 --> 00:08:03.440
and then we fast-forward
to me merging my passion

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:05.790
for the written word with
sports, and deciding,

00:08:05.790 --> 00:08:07.860
I'm going to tell this story.

00:08:07.860 --> 00:08:11.890
And we rewind to the magazine
pitch, to stretching it

00:08:11.890 --> 00:08:14.120
out to become a book proposal.

00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:17.650 position:56%
And the long story short version is,

00:08:17.650 --> 00:08:21.980
spending 10 years putting
this story together.

00:08:21.980 --> 00:08:24.930
And I initially thought
I was embarking

00:08:24.930 --> 00:08:27.190
on a basketball story, right.

00:08:27.190 --> 00:08:31.130
Story of perhaps the greatest high
school basketball team of all time.

00:08:31.130 --> 00:08:33.450
This is the story that
I'm going to tell.

00:08:33.450 --> 00:08:36.810
And so I buried myself
in the archive rooms

00:08:36.810 --> 00:08:41.770
at the Enoch Pratt main library
in Baltimore on Cathedral Street.

00:08:41.770 --> 00:08:44.710
And I said, I have to find
out what was going on.

00:08:44.710 --> 00:08:46.330
I have to look at these games.

00:08:46.330 --> 00:08:48.080
I had to see who did what.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:49.940
Put that together.

00:08:49.940 --> 00:08:54.500 position:56%
But I also said, I need to read the
newspaper from front to back to find

00:08:54.500 --> 00:08:57.320
out what was going on at the time.

00:08:57.320 --> 00:09:02.260
And so it wasn't until I actually
started reading what was going

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:07.180
on in the city and around
the country that I realized,

00:09:07.180 --> 00:09:12.460
this is a basketball story that's
not even about basketball at all.

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:17.330
And so we look at what was
going on in the early 1980s

00:09:17.330 --> 00:09:19.240
in Baltimore at the time.

00:09:19.240 --> 00:09:24.680
And we found this once proud
city really struggling.

00:09:24.680 --> 00:09:29.440
And there were some forces
that were really laying siege

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:31.900
to this once proud community.

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:34.860
Through the head coach Bob
Wade, we kind of get the story

00:09:34.860 --> 00:09:39.500
of his parents being part of
this great northern migration.

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:42.290
They were from a very
small town called Dillwyn,

00:09:42.290 --> 00:09:44.780
Virginia, down South.

00:09:44.780 --> 00:09:49.940
And as we know, the agrarian
economy had ground to a halt.

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:52.680
And a lot of African-American
people were in search

00:09:52.680 --> 00:09:55.360
of the so-called promised land.

00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:59.160
And Bob Wade's parents were
emblematic of the people

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:03.540
who left the tobacco fields and
the cotton fields down South

00:10:03.540 --> 00:10:05.430
in search of the promised land.

00:10:05.430 --> 00:10:09.700
And Baltimore happened to be
one of those promised lands.

00:10:09.700 --> 00:10:16.250
Because due to the World War II
economy, they had iron foundries

00:10:16.250 --> 00:10:22.530 position:56%
and steel mills, the great Bethlehem
Steel complex, car factories.

00:10:22.530 --> 00:10:25.610
They were hiring people
for three shifts a day.

00:10:25.610 --> 00:10:27.920
You didn't have to have
a high level of education

00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:29.750
in order to get a job there.

00:10:29.750 --> 00:10:33.410 position:56%
And the economic prospects were so
much better in cities like Baltimore

00:10:33.410 --> 00:10:36.230
and other cities, that
people migrated to.

00:10:36.230 --> 00:10:40.080
So people were able to
get a decent union wage.

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:42.880
And they were able
to purchase homes.

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:46.230
And they used to scrub those marble
steps in front of those row homes

00:10:46.230 --> 00:10:48.230
in East Baltimore with pride.

00:10:48.230 --> 00:10:51.240
And they dreamed of sending
their kids on to college

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:55.210
and having a better life
for them then they had.

00:10:55.210 --> 00:11:00.020
And so when we fast-forward now
to the early 1980s in Baltimore,

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:02.170
where the book takes place,

00:11:02.170 --> 00:11:07.190
we find that there is the
loss of that union wage.

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:09.670
The way that people were
accustomed to making a living

00:11:09.670 --> 00:11:13.770
and dreaming was no
longer a reality.

00:11:13.770 --> 00:11:17.300
And so Bethlehem Steel, as
I found out as I was going

00:11:17.300 --> 00:11:19.930
through the newspaper
archives of the Baltimore Sun

00:11:19.930 --> 00:11:21.910
and the Baltimore News American,

00:11:21.910 --> 00:11:26.680
were laying people off
at an astounding rate.

00:11:26.680 --> 00:11:29.700
The General Motors plant
was laying off people.

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:33.460
The iron foundries, the steel
mills, the jobs disappeared,

00:11:33.460 --> 00:11:36.470
because the economy changed.

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:42.760 position:56%
And within that, we also had the
onset of the plague of crack cocaine

00:11:42.760 --> 00:11:46.460
at the same time, which
ravaged the community.

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:51.730
Baltimore had long been a town that
was dominated by the heroin trade,

00:11:51.730 --> 00:11:54.390
and the drug business was
always big in Baltimore.

00:11:54.390 --> 00:11:57.610
But there was a very big
shift in the early '80s.

00:11:57.610 --> 00:12:01.790
There was a federal drug
task force that took out all

00:12:01.790 --> 00:12:04.990
of the big-time kingpins
around the heroin trade.

00:12:04.990 --> 00:12:07.020
These guys were older businessmen.

00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:08.320
They were very smart.

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:11.980
They kept it away from
schools, from the outdoors.

00:12:11.980 --> 00:12:13.760
The inventories were regulated.

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:16.060
They ran it like a real business.

00:12:16.060 --> 00:12:21.960
When those guys got taken away,
some gentlemen filled the vacuum.

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:24.730
And they realize that
there were loopholes

00:12:24.730 --> 00:12:27.260
in the city's juvenile
justice system.

00:12:27.260 --> 00:12:30.690
And so what happened was, they
said, if an adult gets caught

00:12:30.690 --> 00:12:33.090
with my stuff, I've got to pay
lawyer fees, they're going to go

00:12:33.090 --> 00:12:34.990
to jail for 10 to 15 years.

00:12:34.990 --> 00:12:37.840
If a kid is younger than 18 and
he's caught selling my stuff,

00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:40.530
he's going to go to a
juvenile detention facility,

00:12:40.530 --> 00:12:44.140
and the next day he's going to
be home with mom and grandma.

00:12:44.140 --> 00:12:49.760
So they started recruiting
teenagers into these drug armies.

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:54.480 position:56%
They created this new business model
called the Open Air Drug Market,

00:12:54.480 --> 00:12:58.230
which ran 24 hours
a day for 20 years.

00:12:58.230 --> 00:13:02.550
And so when you have this army of
undisciplined young people fighting

00:13:02.550 --> 00:13:06.460
over this business where the
profit margins are so astounding,

00:13:06.460 --> 00:13:11.820 position:56%
you have teenagers with a stupefying
amount of semiautomatic weapons,

00:13:11.820 --> 00:13:15.230
random gunfire, a destruction
of the community.

00:13:15.230 --> 00:13:18.500
And all of this stuff
happens around the time

00:13:18.500 --> 00:13:23.160
with this great high school
basketball team comes together.

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:25.700
You have the head coach Bob Wade,

00:13:25.700 --> 00:13:28.830
who was a product of
Dunbar High School.

00:13:28.830 --> 00:13:30.580
He grew up in East Baltimore.

00:13:30.580 --> 00:13:34.520
He himself was a product
of a single-parent home.

00:13:34.520 --> 00:13:39.140
And so he went on to get a college
scholarship to play football.

00:13:39.140 --> 00:13:42.490
Played in the National Football
League for the Washington Redskins,

00:13:42.490 --> 00:13:45.180
the Baltimore Colts,
the Denver Broncos,

00:13:45.180 --> 00:13:47.000
and the Pittsburgh Steelers.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.080
But he was also cognizant
of the fact

00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:53.350
that he had some wonderful mentors
and role models who helped him.

00:13:53.350 --> 00:13:55.510
And while he was in the
National Football League,

00:13:55.510 --> 00:13:59.960
he came back every summer to work
on his teaching certification.

00:13:59.960 --> 00:14:04.780
And his goal was to make an impact
on the young lives of athletes

00:14:04.780 --> 00:14:07.730
in the same way that his
role models did for him.

00:14:07.730 --> 00:14:11.090
He was the valedictorian of
his graduating class at Dunbar.

00:14:11.090 --> 00:14:13.460 position:56%
His mother worked in a textile mill.

00:14:13.460 --> 00:14:17.170
And she always told
him, get your education,

00:14:17.170 --> 00:14:20.360
be serious about your degree,
